  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q011",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "network-devices",
    "stem": "A company that has 2 buildings with different IPs how can I connect them",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Router",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Switch",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Hub",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Bridge",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Two buildings on different IP networks means different subnets, and moving traffic between subnets requires a layer-3 forwarding decision, which is the router's job. Switches, hubs, and bridges operate at layer 1 or 2 and only extend a single broadcast domain, so they cannot join two distinct IP networks.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 11
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "cc957876c81def5b8cb60b57079a18aa187a7a74"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q012",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "mac-addressing",
    "stem": "Ethernet address is?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Unique in ring topology",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Unique locally",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Unique globally",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Not unique",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "An Ethernet (MAC) address is 48 bits: the first 24 are the OUI assigned by the IEEE to a specific vendor, and the last 24 are assigned by that vendor to the card. That two-level allocation is what makes the address globally unique, not merely unique on the local segment.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
